- "garden of ongoing clinical trials" refers to the set of clinical trials that are currently in progress;
- "blossoms" metaphorically refers to the clinical trials;
- "surpassed the threshold of 10,000" indicates that the average BAT value is greater than 10,000;
- "considering only the observations taken more than 10 days after the treatment was administered" means that the observations are from more than 10 days post-treatment.

- "Blood assay test values soaring above 10,000" refers to BAT values greater than 10,000;
- "Liver health test values exceeding 12,000" refers to LH values greater than 12,000;
- "Severe cases" are defined by these high test values indicating critical health conditions.

- 'MTX' is a common abbreviation for Methotrexate, a medication used in various treatments;
- 'Days post-treatment' refers to the number of days after the treatment was administered;
- The first month is typically considered the period from day 1 to day 30 post-treatment.

- A clinical trial is a research study to evaluate the safety and effectiveness of a new medical treatment or intervention.;
- The `agent_name` refers to the name of the drug or treatment being tested in the clinical trial.;
- The `status` of the trial can indicate whether the trial is ongoing, completed, or in another state.;

- "Completed" trials are those that have been successfully concluded;
- "Ethical approval" indicates that the trial has been reviewed and approved by an ethics committee;
- "Compliance rate > 0.8" means that at least 80% of patients adhered to the treatment regimen;
- "BAT" stands for Blood Assay Test, a measure used to assess the effectiveness of a treatment.

- "Elevated blood assay test (BAT) values" refer to BAT > 100;
- "Elevated liver health (LH) test values" refer to LH > 50;
- "Top 3 clinical trials" are those with the highest number of observations.

- Clinical trials are research studies that test new medical interventions, including drugs, to determine their safety and efficacy.;
- The principal investigator is the lead researcher responsible for the conduct of the trial.;
- The route of administration refers to the method by which a treatment is delivered, such as intravenous (IV) or oral.;
- The status of a trial can indicate whether it is ongoing, completed, or in another phase of the research process.

- The term "clinical trials" refers to research studies performed to evaluate the safety and efficacy of new treatments;
- "Blood assay test (BAT)" and "Liver health (LH) test" are specific medical tests used to monitor the health of patients during clinical trials;
- "Rank" is determined by the number of distinct patients in each trial, with 1 being the highest rank;
- "Distinct patients" and "distinct users" refer to unique individuals involved in the trial and accessing the trial data, respectively.

- Cumulative impact refers to the sum of all BAT and LH values recorded over the course of the treatment;
- Blood Assay Test (BAT) and Liver Health (LH) are indicators of the treatment's effectiveness and the patient's health status;
- The most recent observation is determined by the highest `observation_id` value.

- "Top treatment agents" refers to agents with the highest BAT and LH test values, ranked within the top three for each agent;
- "Clinical trials accessed more than once" indicates that the trial has more than one unique access event recorded;
- "More than one observation" ensures that the agent has multiple data points for analysis.

- A high compliance rate is defined as a rate greater than 0.8;
- The success rate is calculated as the percentage of successful treatments out of the total treatments, where a successful treatment is one with a compliance rate greater than 0.8;
- The latest access activity is determined by the most recent access date in the user access logs.
